We wish a very special thank you to all who served in the Vietnam war. We want to pay special tribute to a very dear friend of ours, Tom Eagles, who was an absolute hero, both to America, and to the Vietnamese people he dedicated his life to liberating. Tom passed away several years ago but his legacy still shines bright at NAR. He used to tell stories of tigers eating members of his patrol and surviving strafing runs by Cobra gunships who misidentified his team only because the canon malfunctioned so close to them they could see sparks inside of it from the short. Above all else, Tom was a pure and true believer in his mission. The atrocities committed by the Viet Cong against  those who aided him forever haunted him, as they did to many others who fought alongside him and throughout the conflict. We pause today to remember the sacrifices made by all the American service members who fought in those dark and scary jungles and those who didn’t make it home, both physically and mentally.

#vietnamwar #corpsman #macvsog #forcerecon #mat43 #veteran #vietnamveteran #neverforget

We are proud to support @b.w.r.a.g in this awesome project!

Repost from @b.w.r.a.g

The “WHY” is what drives BWRAG’s mission. After years of seeing close friends pass away in surf accidents, @deepwatersurf and @danilocouto11 felt that enough was enough. There was a gap in ocean safety and surf preparedness that needed to be bridged. 

Fast forward nearly 10 years, guided by the world’s best watermen and women, including @briankeaulana @gerglong @andreamollermaui @healeywaterops @quesopeligroso @americanguard @hargrave, the goal of our Surf Responder Online Course is to provide you with the requisite life-saving training and risk management framework so that you can be a useful asset in an emergency situation. Link in bio to join the global ocean safety movement. We look forward to training with you.

node.text:
We are deeply saddened to hear that CSM Jack Joplin, a true American hero, and legend in the special operations community has passed away. He was an incredible medic and Operator who always put his people first and we are diminished with his passing.

Command Sergeant Major Jack G. Joplin, US Army, was born 23 May 1939 in Bromide, Oklahoma. He joined the US Army in 1961. After completing basic training at Fort Hood, Texas where he trained in infantry skills, he served in the 501st Battle Group, 82nd Airborne Division, and 1st Battalion, 503rd Infantry Regiment, 173 Airborne Brigade. After graduating the Special Forces Qualification Course as a Special Forces Medic, he served in 6th, 3rd, 5th, 1st, and 10th Special Forces Groups, as well as the Special Forces Operational Detachment Delta. From 1967-1991 he provided Non-Commissioned Officer leadership at every level of Special Operations, from Senior Medical Sergeant to Battalion Command Sergeant Major. His service included two tours in Vietnam, as well as overseas assignments in Germany and Okinawa. He participated in Operation Ivory Coast, the attempt to rescue prisoners of war held in the Son Tay prison camp located 23 miles outside of Hanoi. Additionally, in April 1980 he participated in Operation Eagle Claw, the attempt to rescue Americans taken hostage in the wake of the Iranian Revolution. He was the only operator to participate in the Son Tay raid, Operation Eagle Claw, and the invasion of Grenada.

CSM Joplin's awards and decorations include the Silver Star, Bronze Star Medal, Defense Meritorious Service Medal, Army Commendation Medal with "V" and Oak Leaf Cluster, Republic of Vietnam Cross of Gallantry with Palm, Combat Infantry Badge, Combat Medic Badge, Special Forces Tab, and Master Parachutist Badge.

May be an image of military uniform and text that says 'GUERILLA MEDICINE THE SYSTEM (2)'.

Photo by North American Rescue on July 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'THE GUERILLA MED SYSTEM AS WE DISCUSSED IN THE PREVIOUS EPISODE OF THIS SERIES, A STANDARD MEDICAL CHAIN OF CARE WILL BE UNSUSTAINABLE IN ΑΝ UNCONVENTIONAL CONFLICT. INSTEAD, THE CYCLIC MODEL OF CARE, IN WHICH THE GUERILLA FIGHTER IS EVACUATED FROM IMMEDIATE ENEMY PRESSURE, IS STABILIZED AND RECEIVES TREATMENT INSIDE THE AO WILL BE A MAIN POINT OF FOCUS FOR US. REMEMBER THAT THIS IS ONLY PROPOSITION AND THIS MODEL WILL HAVE TO BE CHANGED ON AN INDIVIDUAL BASIS DEPENDING ON OPERATIONAL AND TACTICAL REQUIREMENTS AS WELL AS AVAILABLE CAPABILITIES.'.
Photo by North American Rescue on July 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'POINT OF INJURY/ AREA OF OPERATIONS HOLDING/ REHABILITATION CASUALTY COLLECTION POINT SURGERY'.

Photo by North American Rescue on July 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'GENERAL CONCEPT MEDICINE ON DEMAND AS MEDICAL PROVIDERS WILL BE IN LOW NUMBERS, IT IS VERY LIKELY THAT THERE WILL NOT BE ENOUGH PROVIDERS TO BE AVAILABLE AT ALL TIMES TO SUPPORT GUERILLA OPERATIONS 24/7. ALSO, FIXED MEDICAL SITES ARE A VERY VULNERABLE TARGET FOR ENEMY STRIKES. MOBILITY, FLEXIBILITY AND LOW VISIBILITY WILL NEED TO BE THE PRIORITY OF MEDICAL TEAMS TO ENHANCE SURVIVABILITY. THIS MEANS THAT MEDICAL SUPPORT WILL BE SET UP JUST BEFORE A PLANNED GUERILLA OPERATION AND THEN WILL BE DISMANTLED IMMEDIATELY AFTERWARDS AGAIN. THIS WILL REQUIRE COORDINATION AND INFORMATION EXCHANGE WITH THE ACTIVE GUERILLA ELEMENT.'.

Photo by North American Rescue on July 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'IMMEDIATE CARE TO ENHANCE THE CHANCE OF SURVIVAL, ALL GUERILLAS SHOULD HAVE BASIC TCCC TRAINING. ORGANIC MEDICAL ASSETS OF THE GUERILLA FORCE WILL VERY LIKELY BE LIMITED TO COMBAT LIFESAVER-STYLE PROVIDERS WITHOUT INSTITUTIONAL MEDICAL TRAINING. WE WILL TALK ABOUT THIS IN DEPTH IN THE NEXT EPISODE. THE ROLE OF THE GUERILLA CLS WILL BE TO PROVIDE IMMEDIATE CARE TO CASUALTIES PROVIDING BASIC EN-ROUTE CARE UNTIL THEY CAN REACH A CASUALTY COLLECTION POINT (CCP) AND ASSIST MEDICS IN PROVIDING CARE AT THE CCP.'.

Photo by North American Rescue on July 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'ADVANCED CARE AT THE ccp, THE GUERILLA CLS WILL HAND THE CASUALTY OVER TO AN ADVANCED PROVIDER LIKE A CERTIFIED MEDIC OR SIMILAR. THERE CASUALTIES WILL BE TRIAGED, FURTHER TREATED AND THEN EVACUATED TO APPROPRIATE ASSETS LIKE SURGICAL TEAMS OR HOLDING TEAMS. RAPID TRANSPORT AWAY FROM THE CCP WILL DECREASE DETECTION AND PREVENT OVERLOADING THE CCP.'.

Photo by North American Rescue on July 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'DEFINITIVE CARE THE TRIAGED AND STABILIZED CASUALTIES WILL THEN EITHER ARRIVE AT FORWARD SURGICAL TEAMS OR AT SO-CALLED HOLDING TEAMS, THAT WILL PROVIDE LONGER-TERM CARE TO THOSE CASUALTIES AFTER SURGERY OR THAT DO NOT REQUIRE SURGERY. IT IS HIGHLY RECOMMENDED THAT MULTIPLE FORWARD SURGICAL TEAMS WOULD BE DISTRIBUTED THROUGHOUT THE AO TO MAKE TRACKING THE CASUALTY FLOW MORE DIFFICULT FOR THE ENEMY AND DECREASE WAITING TIMES FOR INCOMING PATIENTS.'.

Photo by North American Rescue on July 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'IN THE NEXT EPISODE, WE WILL DISCUSS HOW THE INDIVIDUAL PARTS OF THIS CHAIN OF CARE COULD BE SET UP AND WHAT A FIELD CLINIC COULD LOOK LIKE. ALSO, WE HAVE A LITTLE BONUS IN STORE FOR YOU GUYS. SOMETHING THAT WILL HOPEFULLY BE USEFUL FOR A LOT OF PEOPLE AROUND THE WORLD. STAY TUNED ALSO, CHECK OUT OUR DISCORD SERVER TO KEEP IN TOUCH WITH THE COMMUNITY. LINK IN BIO'.

AFTER He IS THEN EITHER ΤΟ LRMC IN GERMANY OR TO THE UNITED STATES FOR REHABILITATION.'.

AT THE MOMENT, WE HAVE TOTAL AIR SUPERIORITY THAT USUALLY ALLOWS US TO CALL IN EVAC AT ANY POINT IN TIME WE DESIRE. 2. WE HAVE LARGE FIELD HOSPITALS AND FORWARD SURGICAL TEAMS THAT WE CAN DELIVER A PATIENT TO. 3. WE HAVE MEDICAL CAPABILITIES THAT USUALLY EXCEED THE "DEMANDS" BOTH IN EQUIPMENT QUALITY AND AVAILABILITY.'.

Photo by North American Rescue on July 20, 2021. IN THE NEXT PART OF THE SERIES WE WILL DIVE DEEPER INTO HOW THIS GUERILLA MEDICAL SYSTEM COULD LOOK LIKE, WHAT CURRENT CIVILIAN MEDICAL PRACTITIONERS COULD DO TO PREPARE THEMSELVES FOR THIS KIND OF SCENARIO AND WHAT REGULAR CIVILIANS COULD DO TO BECOME AN ASSET FOR THEIR PEOPLE, WHEN THE TIME COMES.'.

node.text:
Medical Monday from @eunomiajournal

From the inbox: what is the most relevant skill you have used overseas? 

Surprisingly despite the current PMT, trauma medicine won’t take up 90% of your deployment. Clinical medicine has a significant role in your duty as an independent practitioner. 

1. Muscle-skeletal injuries from dudes hitting the deployment gym too hard. taking “supplements” from steers. Picking up weight, they have no business picking up. Be familiar with teaching mobility training, dynamic stretching, and recovery techniques. 

2. Dental injuries will also be a factor; dental injuries can render a team mission incapable. They're allowed to keep a dip in, but make sure they follow up with proper dental hygiene. 

3. Cellulitis or skin infections from people using improper hygiene overseas. Travelers diarrhea, ETC. Keep pills handy in your drug box during long missions. 

4. Administering essential physical exams and tests will take up your time Ortho, hearing, TBI, COVID, Malaria, ETC. 

5. Always have bandaids. 

All these are skills not related to trauma but skills that will take up most of your deployed time. Make sure you take some time, even if it has to be on your own, to stay sharp on clinical medicine. For every combat casualty, you treat. You’ll have 20-50 sick-call patients you also treat. Big thanks to the BDE dentist for the training and resources. #army #civilaffairs #w4 #socm #sotm #medic #combatmedic #medicine #medicine  #medical #medicalmonday #medicalschool #future #warrior #doc #read #learn #psyops #usasoc #ussocom #swcs #dental #clinical

How to approach Monday…from @wildernessdoctor
•
Pay attention to how calmly he grabs his reserve parachute - he even practices a throw before releasing.

Having seen medical providers and rescue workers in these scenarios; I can tell you that practice and preparation is key to success in saving the patient’s life or even your own.

We practice what we hope to never see and know what we see daily by heart. This is what defines rescue workers and emergency providers as professionals.

This video highlights these characteristics, perfectly and like a knife must always be re-sharpened.

Keep Safe and Stay Vigilant!
